{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14336"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14336"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.12,0.31,0.16,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7031"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40229"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3747"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19325"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-kg child has lost 400 mL of blood and is haemodynamically unstable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best represents the percentage of total blood volume this child has lost?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["50%","60%","40%","30%","20%"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETo determine the percentage of total blood volume lost, we first need to calculate the child\u0027s total blood volume and then compare the volume lost to this total.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe average total blood volume for a child is approximately 80 mL/kg of body weight. For a 10-kg child:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal blood volume = 10 kg \u00d7 80 mL/kg = 800 mL\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe child has lost 400 mL of blood. To calculate the percentage:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E(400 mL / 800 mL) \u00d7 100 = 50%\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, this child has lost \u003Cstrong\u003E50%\u003C/strong\u003E of their total blood volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA loss of \u003Cstrong\u003E20%\u003C/strong\u003E or more of total blood volume typically results in haemodynamic instability in children, which aligns with the child\u0027s condition in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E30%\u003C/strong\u003E loss would be 240 mL, which is less than the stated 400 mL loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E40%\u003C/strong\u003E loss would be 320 mL, also less than the actual loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E60%\u003C/strong\u003E loss would be 480 mL, which is more than the stated 400 mL loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis significant blood loss (50% of total volume) explains why the child is haemodynamically unstable and requires immediate medical attention. Such a severe loss is life-threatening and necessitates urgent fluid resuscitation and blood transfusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A child\u0027s total blood volume is approximately 80 mL/kg of body weight.","Loss of 20% or more of total blood volume typically results in haemodynamic instability in children.","A 50% loss of total blood volume is a critical emergency requiring immediate intervention."],"references":["Howie SR. Blood sample volumes in child health research: review of safe limits. Bull World Health Organ. 2011 Jan 1;89(1):46-53. doi: 10.2471/BLT.10.080010. Epub 2010 Sep 10. PMID: 21346890; PMCID: PMC3040020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40229"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14336"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40229"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T14:38:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T14:39:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7031"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54700"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"On